      <h2 id="about-me">About Me</h2>

<p> üëã Hi, I am Xinyue Chen,  a fifth-year Ph.D. candidate in <a href="https://cse.engin.umich.edu/" class="bold">Computer Science and Engineering</a> at the <a href="https://umich.edu/" class="bold">University of Michigan</a>, advised by <a href="https://web.eecs.umich.edu/~xwanghci/" class="bold">Prof. Xu Wang</a>.</p>

<p>My research sits at the intersection of <strong>Human‚ÄìComputer Interaction (HCI)</strong>, <strong>Human‚ÄìAI Interaction</strong>, and <strong>Cognitive Science</strong>, investigating how AI can scaffold human sense-making across individual and collaborative contexts. My work has been published in premier venues including CHI, CSCW, DIS, and AIED, and has received several Best Paper Honorable Mention Awards. Together, my work contributes to a broader vision of AI systems that support human cognition, advance mechanisms for human‚ÄìAI alignment and AI-mediated common ground, helping people and teams think, learn, and coordinate more effectively with and through AI.</p>

<p>Prior to Michigan, I received my B.S. in Information Management from <a href="https://www.pku.edu.cn/" class="bold">Peking University</a>, advised by <a href="https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=fL6FUdkAAAAJ&amp;hl=en" class="bold">Prof. Pengyi Zhang</a>. I have also worked as a Research Scientist Intern at <a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/lab/microsoft-research-cambridge/" class="bold">Microsoft Research Cambridge</a> (Tools for Thought group, mentored by <a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/people/serintel/">Sean Rintel</a>, <a href="https://www.levtankelevitch.com/">Lev Tankelevitch</a>, and <a href="https://payodpanda.com/">Payod Panda</a>) and <strong>Adobe Research</strong> (Document Intelligence team, mentored by <a href="https://research.adobe.com/person/alexa-siu/">Alexa Siu</a> and <a href="https://research.adobe.com/person/tong-sun/">Tong Sun</a>).</p>

<h2 id="research-overview"> Research Overview</h2>

<p>In knowledge-intensive tasks such as analysis, writing, learning, and collaboration, people engage in continuous sense-making‚Äîrefining understanding as they work and learn. As AI becomes embedded in these processes, my research asks:</p>

<p class="research-hook">How can AI assist without weakening the human sense-making these tasks rely on?</p>

<p>In collaborative settings, such as meetings and co-writing, I design AI-mediated systems that visualize and scaffold human‚Äìhuman common ground, making shared understanding visible and actionable. In individual tasks, I study human‚ÄìAI alignment and propose intermediate AI designs that balance assistance with agency, helping people stay cognitively engaged while enabling AI to adapt through interaction.</p>

<p>Together, these studies advance a vision of <strong>AI-mediated common ground</strong>, where humans and AI co-construct understanding through ongoing collaboration.</p>

<h2 id="research-interests">üîç Research Interests</h2>

<p>Human‚ÄìAI Collaboration ¬∑ Cognitive Augmentation ¬∑ AI-Mediated Communication ¬∑ Sense-Making and Reasoning ¬∑ Collaborative Learning ¬∑ Human-Centered AI</p>

